definition.value: Propaganda based on homonegativity and homophobia towards homosexual and sometimes other non-heterosexual people. Such propaganda supports anti-gay prejudices and stereotypes, and promotes social stigmatization or discrimination.
Propaganda based on transphobia towards transgender people. Such propaganda supports anti-transgender prejudices and stereotypes, and promotes social stigmatization or discrimination.
Suicides organized by a particularly victimized group committing such an act.
Suicides organized by some categorical typing that isn't by method.
Suicides of LGBTQIA+ persons, particular those related to such a victim's identification as LGBTQIA+ and social discrimination based on such status.
Suicides as they occur among LGBTQIA+ youth.
Suicides as they occur among transgender people.
A planned series of media intended to achieve a particular purpose or purposes.
A media campaign that aims to increase public awareness of a particular issue or topic.
A media campaign that aims to increase public awareness of LGBTQIA+ civil and human rights issues.
Any of various tests involved with the field of sexology or tests related to the inquiries made in sexology.
Any of various pseudoscientific tests or proposed hypothetical tests which claim to be able to elucidate whether or not a person is gay.
Homicide which constitutes a crime under a particular legal system.
The unlawful killing of another human without justification or valid excuse, especially the unlawful killing of another human with malice aforethought.
A common law legal term for homicide considered by law as less culpable than murder. The definition of manslaughter differs among legal jurisdictions.
The homicide of a human being without intent of doing so, either expressed or implied. It is distinguished from voluntary manslaughter by the absence of intention.

The killing of a human being in which the offender acted during the heat of passion, under circumstances that would cause a reasonable person to become emotionally or mentally disturbed to the point that they can't reasonably control their emotions.

Manslaughter which occurs when someone kills, without intent, in the course of committing an unlawful act. The malice involved in the crime is transferred to the killing, resulting in a charge of manslaughter.

Manslaughter which occurs where death results from serious negligence, or, in some jurisdictions, serious recklessness. A high degree of negligence is required to warrant criminal liability. A related concept is that of willful blindness, which is where a defendant intentionally puts themself in a position where the defendant will be unaware of facts which would render them liable.
Murders organized by degree or severity under various legal systems.

A label used in many states in the United States to describe any intentional murder that is willful and premeditated with malice aforethought. Felony murder, a charge that may be filed against a defendant who is involved in a dangerous crime where a death results from the crime, is typically first-degree.
A label used in many states in the United States to describe any intentional murder with malice aforethought, but is not premeditated or planned in advance.
Homicides classified by degree of lawfulness or unlawfulness of the act.
Homicides organized by the victim or victims characteristics, etc.
The homicide of an individual who is a child.
Murders organized primarily by the victim or victims involved.
Murders of children; murder in which a child or children are the primary victims.
Murders organized by the number of victims involved.

The act of murdering a number of people, typically simultaneously or over a relatively short period of time and in close geographic proximity. The FBI defines mass murder as murdering four or more persons during an event with no "cooling-off period" between the murders.
A murder in a sequence of murders which each take place over more than a month and include a significant period of time between them.
Homicides categorized by method, either of contact of the victim or by the weapon or weapons involved in the homicide itself.
Homicide in which the victim and perpetrator met online, in some cases having known each other previously only through the internet.
A mass murder in which victims were primarily shot.
A mass murder in which victims were primarily stabbed.
Homicide of a gay person in which the person's attitudes toward gay people ultimately resulted in the homicide.
Homicide of a lesbian in which the person's attitudes toward lesbians ultimately resulted in the homicide.
Homicide of a transgender person in which the person's attitudes toward transgender people ultimately resulted in the homicide.
A prejudice-motivated crime which occurs when a perpetrator targets a victim because of their membership (or perceived membership) in the LGBTQIA+ community.

An over-generalized belief about a particular category of people. It is an expectation that people might have about every person of a particular group. The type of expectation can vary; it can be, for example, an expectation about the group's personality, preferences, or ability.

Conventional, formulaic generalizations, opinions, or images based on the sexual orientations or gender identities of LGBTQIA+ people. Stereotypical perceptions may be acquired through interactions with parents, teachers, peers and mass media, or, more generally, through a lack of firsthand familiarity, resulting in an increased reliance on generalizations.
Stereotypes related to a person's gender.
Conventional, formulaic generalizations, opinions, or images concerning men.
Conventional, formulaic generalizations, opinions, or images concerning women.

The bias or perceived bias of scholars allowing their beliefs to shape their research and the scientific community. It can refer to several types of scholastic prejudice i.e. logocentrism, phonocentrism, ethnocentrism or the belief that some sciences and disciplines rank higher than other.

The bias or perceived bias of journalists and news producers within the mass media in the selection of many events and stories that are reported and how they are covered. The term "media bias" implies a pervasive or widespread bias contravening the standards of journalism, rather than the perspective of an individual journalist or article. The direction and degree of media bias in various countries is widely disputed.
Domestic violence by a current or former partner in an intimate relationship against the same-sex partner.
Domestic violence by a current or former partner in an intimate relationship against the different-sex partner.
Domestic violence by a current or former partner in an intimate gay male relationship against the partner.
Domestic violence by a current or former partner in an intimate lesbian relationship against the partner.
A person who has suffered from any of various forms of abuse.
